Raw dev notes -- Taming the Colab Beast for a RAG Pipeline

Okay, so this project, let's call it the "Rav Oury Cherki RAG pipeline," is all about making the teachings of Rav Oury Cherki more accessible. The idea is to build a Retrieval Augmented Generation (RAG) system that can answer questions based on his vast body of work. It's a personal passion project, trying to leverage LLMs for something meaningful to me.

This past week or so has been a whirlwind, mostly wrestling with environments and getting the data ingestion pipeline solid. The initial commit was just getting the basic RAG idea down, but then the real work began. A huge chunk of my time went into making this whole thing runnable in Google Colab. Seriously, Colab is a beast. I had to pin `lightning-fabric` to a specific version, deal with some weird `partial-numpy` swaps after an install cascade, and switch to `%pip` magic because regular `pip` was causing issues. Then there were the "runtime shims" – basically, little patches to make things like `torchaudio.info` and even `numpy.NAN` play nice in the Colab environment. It felt like I was constantly patching holes in a leaky boat.

Beyond the Colab environment hell, I made some good progress on the actual data pipeline. I built out `playlist recovery` to grab content from various sources, a `WhatsApp chat parser` (which was surprisingly tricky), and a `name-variation search` to help consolidate different spellings or references. There's also a `batch diarize notebook` now, which is crucial for processing audio, and I even started looking into the Colab API for more programmatic control. Getting a `GDrive downloader` working was a big win too, as a lot of the source material lives there. I also added `candidate review tools` to help check the quality of the processed data and fixed some issues with `needs_transcription` regeneration during cleanup.

The hardest part, hands down, was the Colab environment. Every time I thought I had it stable, something else would break. The `numpy` issues were particularly frustrating, and trying to get `pyannote` (for diarization) to work consistently across different Colab runtimes and local `venv` setups was a nightmare. I spent a lot of time exploring `venv` theory just to understand why things were breaking. Another unexpected snag was with URL shorteners – I had to bypass SSL certificate verification for some of them just to follow redirects, which felt a bit hacky but necessary to get the data.

But, man, when I finally got a "successful E2E run" – that was a huge relief. It felt like climbing a mountain and finally seeing the view. All those little fixes, the constant debugging, the moments of wanting to throw my laptop across the room... it paid off. It really hammered home the importance of persistence and how much time can be sucked into environment setup, even on seemingly simple projects. It's a good reminder that the "glamorous" AI stuff often sits on a foundation of gritty, low-level engineering. I learned a ton about dependency management and the quirks of cloud notebooks.

Next up: Focus on improving the RAG retrieval quality and expanding the data sources.
